According to legend, {{ill|Gyōki|ja|行基|qq=draft|qq=draft}} received a revelation in a dream saying, "This mountain is a peerless sacred land. Establish a temple here, practice the three mysteries of {{ill|yoga|ja|瑜伽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and worship me as Yuga Daigongen." Following this revelation, Gyōki founded the temple on the mountain in the fifth year of {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (733 CE). He enshrined Amida Nyorai and Yakushi Nyorai, marking the beginning of the Yuga Daigongen faith.<ref>Rendaiji Engi (Temple Record).</ref> 

The faith further developed when Yuga Mountain was referred to as "New Kumano Nachisan," aligning with the {{ill|Five Schools of Shugendō|ja|五流修験道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. According to the records of the Five Streams’ Honzan-based {{ill|Goryū Sontakuin|ja|五流尊瀧院|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the mountain's temples—Rendaiji (Nachisan), Goryū Sontakuin (Hongū), and Shokōji (Shingū)—were collectively known as the "New Kumano Gongen Three Shrines."

== Overview ==
Yuga Daigongen is known as the "Deity of Disaster Prevention." The deity was deeply revered by successive lords of the {{ill|Okayama Domain|ja|岡山藩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, starting with [[:en:Ikeda_Tsugumasa|Ikeda Tsugumasa]]. It also became one of the most significant pilgrimage destinations in the {{ill|Seto Inland Sea|ja|瀬戸内海|qq=draft|qq=draft}} region. Alongside {{ill|Konpira Daigongen|ja|金毘羅大権現|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was worshiped as one half of the "Dual Pilgrimage," with devotees visiting both shrines once in their lifetime to pray for the fulfillment of their wishes.<ref name="yugasan">[http://www.yugasan.jp/engi.html Yugasan Rendaiji – Historical Record]</ref>

== Shinbutsu Bunri and Haibutsu Kishaku ==
The {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft}} order of 1868, followed by the {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|1=Haibutsu kishaku|qq=draft|qq=draft}} movement, led to the abolition of Yuga Daigongen as a Shugendō deity. Although {{ill|Yugasan Rendaiji|ja|瑜伽山蓮台寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} narrowly avoided closure in 1873, it was forcibly separated into the {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|ja|真言宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}}-affiliated Rendaiji and the {{ill|Yuga Shrine|ja|由加神社本宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== See Also ==
* {{ill|Yuga Mountain|ja|由加山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

